The last game i played that I didn't enjoy enjoy FIFA 23. The reasons that lead to such lack of enjoyment were the fact that the game is driven to make the user spend real money to truly progress in game, the gameplay being inconsistent and feeling un-rewarding and the removal of progression strategies present in previous iterations of the franchise, that were fundamental for players who didn't want to spend money on the game. This made me feel sad, as I wasn't able to enjoy a franchise I've played for over a decade, disappointed in the current trajectory of the game and cheated, because as a customer I was made to believe the game would be very different and AT LEAST as good as the previous one.

Most recent game I remember not enjoying was "The Outer Worlds", by Obsidian Entertainment.
The game was overly hyped before its release, since it was being developed by people who had worked on a very good RPG game, popular for having the best story out of that game's last three installments (Fallout New Vegas).
As such, I expected good writing in "The Outer Worlds", or at least anything unique on it that could hold me in and entertain. Instead I got your average sci-fi "Rich people are always the evil cruel monsters! The rebels were actually the good guys!" story that felt too much like a clear propaganda. That combined with the fact the NPCs all had the same punchable smug face, and gameplay being "Meh" as a typical "adventure FPS".
The issue wasn't the game being political, the issue was the game was very poorly written accompanied by clearly forced choices, with a tedious repetitive gameplay, soul-less characters, and a horrible inventory management.

I felt like I was doing a chore the entire game, without any real improvements throughout it.

The most recent game that I've played is CS:GO. In fact, you could say I'm a veteran player, as I've played that game for over 3000 hours (according to my Steam profile). So me and my teammates played a competitive match on a map called "Anubis" (kind of a new map), and we managed to win 16-13 (that match took around 40 minutes). The best thing about competitive games is the "flow" state that they allow you to enter. That is something I usually experience a few times per match. Especially in emotionally charged situations. That "flow" makes me somehow connected to the game on a psychic level. My field of view shrinks a bit, which lets me focus on the game more, my reaction time gets way faster, and I completely cut off all the stimuli outside of the game. You should read about that, it's sort of a common thing for pro players, and that might be helpful for your study.

I play video games very regularly, in long sessions. The last time I played a computer game for at least 20 minutes was yesterday. My friends and I played GTA Online. We come back to this game from time to time to spend time together. The game is not about some predetermined activities, and above all about spending time together, where the game is simply the background.
This time we restocked parcel warehouses to later sell them as a group. I felt great during these activities, but it was mainly because of this opportunity to interact with friends. The gameplay itself would seem boring to most.
There are many such games in which I immerse myself and feel full immersion, such as Red Dead Redemption, in which I spent hundreds of hours and completed this game many times.
I also like games that are seemingly boring to most people, such as ETS. When I'm driving in ETS, I like to listen to the radio and watch the scenery. It is also a time when I can talk to someone, e.g. on discord, or watch a video on YouTube or Netflix.
Anyway, games are all about having fun. The point is that every game user should be able to use them in any way that makes them happy, as long as it does not interfere with the fun of other people.

Recently, while playing Gothic, I decided to try my hand at fighting one of the toughest opponents - the dragon. After many hours of gathering the best equipment and preparations, I finally came face to face with the beast. It was a truly epic battle in which I had to use all my skills and experience to survive. Fortunately, after much hardship and sacrifice, I managed to defeat the dragon. I was really happy with this success and felt like a real hero. I like this game because it has a great storyline, interesting characters and a world that you can explore and discover in any way you want. In addition, Gothic has a unique graphical style and music that perfectly sets the mood of the game world. One aspect that can be improved in Gothic is the artificial intelligence of the enemies. Sometimes they seem too easy to defeat or too predictable. Also, some missions are too difficult or unintuitive, which may discourage some players. However, despite these imperfections, I think Gothic is one of the best RPGs and I will always have a fondness for this title.

recallText: It´s an online tactical shooter game. I like the game because of it's realism, and could be improved if it had more playable vehicles

My last three matches were a roaring success. The biggest selling point is the staggering amount of vehicles, both land and aircraft that the game has. The game is free to play but extremely content rich. The monetisation could be improved, and the progress grind can get on your nerves if you don't pace yourself.

I have been trying to get a legendary (highest tier) accessory which is obtained by completing numerous achievements in specific maps in the game. Occasionally random events happen and organised group events also happen, such as raids or other guild events. 

What I enjoy most about the game is the "horizontal progression", which means that upon reaching the maximum level (80) of a character, this progress will not be diminished by future releases, rather new content simply adds on to your characters and what they can do, which is different to most MMOs where generally new content means older content is less or no longer relevant.

The game is of course by no means perfect, and a lot of the menus and navigation seems very dated compared to other games, and the lack of addons available mean you can see or analyze your performance a lot less compared to other games. This can definitely take some getting used to and is certainly frustrating at times
